    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-05-04T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-05-04T03:00:00-05:00" n="391"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d391">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">550.S1 Washington/356: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gordon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-05-04T09:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 4, 1933—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 4—6:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>73. My telegram No. 66, April 26.<note n="28" xml:id="d391fn28">Not
                        printed.</note> Although I cannot state it as a fact, I have recently had
                    some reason to believe that whereas, prior to Hitler’s coming into power and at
                    the inception of the present regime, Schacht<note n="29" xml:id="d391fn29"
                        >Hjalmar Schacht, President of the German Reiehsbank.</note> doubtless
                    occupied the role of a very independent adviser to Hitler, he is now becoming
                    increasingly subject to the pressure of the Nazi steam roller. In other words
                    whereas he formerly was perhaps able to tell Hitler that he should adopt this or
                    that policy it now may well be that if Schacht himself wishes to take such and
                    such measures he has to secure consent not only of the Chancellor but also even
                    of Goering.</p>
                <p>I send the foregoing for what it may be worth in connection with forthcoming
                    conversations with Schacht.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gordon</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
